---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import { SITE } from "../../config/site";
import { amortizationSchedule } from "../../lib/calc/loan";

const title = "Refinance Break-even (how to estimate it)";
const description =
  "A refinance break-even estimate compares monthly savings to closing costs and how long you plan to keep the loan. Educational use only.";

const examplePrincipal = 300000;
const exampleCurrentApr = 6.5;
const exampleCurrentTerm = 360;
const exampleRefiApr = 5.75;
const exampleRefiTerm = 360;
const exampleClosingCosts = 6000;
const current = amortizationSchedule({
  principal: examplePrincipal,
  aprPercent: exampleCurrentApr,
  termMonths: exampleCurrentTerm
});
const refi = amortizationSchedule({
  principal: examplePrincipal,
  aprPercent: exampleRefiApr,
  termMonths: exampleRefiTerm
});
const monthlySavings = Math.max(0, current.paymentPI - refi.paymentPI);
const breakevenMonths = monthlySavings > 0 ? exampleClosingCosts / monthlySavings : null;
const breakevenMonthsRounded = breakevenMonths == null ? null : Math.ceil(breakevenMonths);
const breakevenYears = breakevenMonthsRounded == null ? null : breakevenMonthsRounded / 12;
const lowClosingCosts = 4000;
const highClosingCosts = 8000;
const breakevenLow = monthlySavings > 0 ? lowClosingCosts / monthlySavings : null;
const breakevenHigh = monthlySavings > 0 ? highClosingCosts / monthlySavings : null;
const yearsMonths = (months: number | null) => {
  if (months == null) return null;
  const rounded = Math.ceil(months);
  return { years: Math.floor(rounded / 12), months: rounded % 12, total: rounded };
};
const breakevenYm = yearsMonths(breakevenMonths);
const breakevenLowYm = yearsMonths(breakevenLow);
const breakevenHighYm = yearsMonths(breakevenHigh);
const money0 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD", minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 0 });
const money2 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { style: "currency", currency: "USD", minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
const pct2 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { minimumFractionDigits: 2, maximumFractionDigits: 2 });
const num1 = new Intl.NumberFormat("en-US", { minimumFractionDigits: 0, maximumFractionDigits: 1 });
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/guides/refinance-break-even">
  <section class="card hero">
    <span class="pill">Guide</span>
    <nav class="breadcrumbs" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
      <a href="/">Home</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <a href="/guides">Guides</a>
      <span aria-hidden="true">/</span>
      <span aria-current="page">Refinance break-even</span>
    </nav>
    <h1>Refinance break-even</h1>
    <p>
      Break-even is the point where your monthly savings from a refinance have "paid back" the closing costs. It's a
      useful sanity check, but it depends on your rate, term, costs, taxes, and how long you'll keep the mortgage.
    </p>
    <div class="btn-row">
      <a class="btn" href="/topics/mortgage-payoff">Mortgage payoff topic hub</a>
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/mortgage-payment-calculator">Compare monthly payments</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/amortization-schedule-calculator">Compare schedules</a>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">A simple break-even formula</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      A common first-pass estimate is:
    </p>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Monthly savings = old monthly payment - new monthly payment (keep assumptions consistent).</li>
      <li>Break-even months = closing costs / monthly savings.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      If you plan to move or refinance again before break-even, refinancing may not make sense. If you'll keep the loan
      longer, a refinance can be beneficial even if break-even takes a while.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Worked example (computed)</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Example: {money0.format(examplePrincipal)} mortgage at {pct2.format(exampleCurrentApr)}% vs refinance at {pct2.format(exampleRefiApr)}%
      with {money0.format(exampleClosingCosts)} in closing costs, both 30-year terms.
    </p>
    <div style="overflow:auto; margin-top:12px">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Scenario</th>
            <th class="num">Rate</th>
            <th class="num">Term</th>
            <th class="num">Monthly P&amp;I</th>
            <th class="num">Total interest</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Current</td>
            <td class="num">{pct2.format(exampleCurrentApr)}%</td>
            <td class="num">{exampleCurrentTerm} mo</td>
            <td class="num">{money2.format(current.paymentPI)}</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(current.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Refi</td>
            <td class="num">{pct2.format(exampleRefiApr)}%</td>
            <td class="num">{exampleRefiTerm} mo</td>
            <td class="num">{money2.format(refi.paymentPI)}</td>
            <td class="num">{money0.format(refi.totalInterest)}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Monthly savings are about {money2.format(monthlySavings)}. Break-even is roughly{" "}
      <strong>{breakevenYm == null ? "N/A" : `${num1.format(breakevenYm.total)} months`}</strong>
      {breakevenYm == null ? "" : ` (${breakevenYm.years}y ${breakevenYm.months}m)`}.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Break-even sensitivity (costs)</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Small changes in closing costs can shift break-even by months. Use this table to see how sensitive the estimate is to fees.
    </p>
    <div style="overflow:auto; margin-top:12px">
      <table class="table">
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Closing costs</th>
            <th class="num">Break-even (months)</th>
            <th class="num">Break-even (years)</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>{money0.format(lowClosingCosts)}</td>
            <td class="num">{breakevenLowYm == null ? "N/A" : `${num1.format(breakevenLowYm.total)} months`}</td>
            <td class="num">{breakevenLowYm == null ? "N/A" : `${breakevenLowYm.years}y ${breakevenLowYm.months}m`}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>{money0.format(exampleClosingCosts)}</td>
            <td class="num">{breakevenYm == null ? "N/A" : `${num1.format(breakevenYm.total)} months`}</td>
            <td class="num">{breakevenYm == null ? "N/A" : `${breakevenYm.years}y ${breakevenYm.months}m`}</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>{money0.format(highClosingCosts)}</td>
            <td class="num">{breakevenHighYm == null ? "N/A" : `${num1.format(breakevenHighYm.total)} months`}</td>
            <td class="num">{breakevenHighYm == null ? "N/A" : `${breakevenHighYm.years}y ${breakevenHighYm.months}m`}</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="grid" style="margin-top:18px">
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">What can change results</h2>
      <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
        <li>Loan term resets (30-year refi vs remaining term).</li>
        <li>Points vs rate trade-off (upfront cost vs lower rate).</li>
        <li>Rolling costs into the loan (affects balance and interest).</li>
        <li>Taxes and deductions (if applicable).</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="card section prose col-6">
      <h2 style="margin-top:0">Refi vs extra principal</h2>
      <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
        If your rate is already low, extra principal payments can be a simpler path: no closing costs, and you can stop
        any time. If rates dropped materially, refinancing may outperform extra payments over the same horizon.
      </p>
      <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:12px">
        <a class="btn" href="/calculators/extra-payment-calculator">Extra principal scenarios</a>
        <a class="btn" href="/guides/pay-off-mortgage-early-or-invest">Pay off early or invest?</a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Costs to include in break-even</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>Lender fees:</strong> origination, underwriting, and processing.</li>
      <li><strong>Points:</strong> paid to buy down the rate (optional).</li>
      <li><strong>Third-party costs:</strong> appraisal, title, recording, and escrow fees.</li>
      <li><strong>Prepaid items:</strong> interest, taxes, and insurance that affect cash-to-close.</li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Some of these costs are unavoidable, while others are optional. A lower rate can be attractive, but if you pay high points you need a
      long enough horizon to recoup them.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Break-even vs total cost</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0">
      Break-even focuses on how long it takes to recoup closing costs through monthly savings. But total cost can tell a different story if
      you reset to a new 30-year term or pay large points upfront.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      A refinance with a lower payment might still cost more in total interest if it extends the term significantly. Always compare the
      total interest over your expected time horizon, not just the monthly payment.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Statement check</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Use the note rate on your statement, not a blended APR.</li>
      <li>Confirm the remaining term in months (not the original term).</li>
      <li>Match the closing cost list to the Loan Estimate fee breakdown.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">How to compare with these tools</h2>
    <ol class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>Compute your current monthly payment and baseline amortization.</li>
      <li>Compute the refinance monthly payment using the new rate/term/fees assumptions.</li>
      <li>Compare total interest and the time horizon you actually expect to hold the loan.</li>
    </ol>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:12px">
      <a class="btn btn-primary" href="/calculators/mortgage-payment-calculator">Mortgage payment</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/amortization-schedule-calculator">Amortization schedule</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/mortgage-recast-vs-extra-payments">Recast vs extra payments</a>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">
      Questions? Email <a href={`mailto:${SITE.email}`}>{SITE.email}</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">Checklist: before you decide</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li><strong>Confirm remaining term:</strong> compare against the term you actually have left.</li>
      <li><strong>Itemize closing costs:</strong> lender fees, points, and third-party costs.</li>
      <li><strong>Decide cash vs roll-in:</strong> rolling costs raises the balance and interest.</li>
      <li><strong>Estimate time horizon:</strong> if you plan to move within a few years, break-even matters more.</li>
      <li><strong>Compare total interest:</strong> not just the monthly payment.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">FAQ</h2>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Is break-even the only thing that matters?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      No. Break-even is a useful checkpoint, but your total interest, cash-to-close, and expected time horizon often matter more.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Should I reset to 30 years to lower the payment?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      It can lower the payment, but it may increase total interest. Consider a shorter term or make extra principal payments if you want to
      avoid extending the payoff timeline.
    </p>
    <h3 style="margin:12px 0 0">Are points worth it?</h3>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:8px 0 0">
      Points can reduce the rate but increase upfront cost. Use break-even math to see if the monthly savings justify the cost given how
      long you plan to keep the loan.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card section prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">References</h2>
    <ul class="muted" style="margin:10px 0 0; padding-left:18px">
      <li>
        CFPB:{" "}
        <a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/consumer-tools/mortgages/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank">
          Mortgages resources
        </a>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0">Educational use only. Not financial advice.</p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:12px 0 0; font-size:13px">Last updated: 2026-01-29</p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
